{
  "comment_text": {
    "sn9.14:2.3": "This is, of course, poetry. In the Vinaya, to be theft it must be something someone owns, and they must perceive it as taken and lost to them. ",
    "sn9.14:3.3": "<i lang='pi' translate='no'>Kena vaṇṇena</i> is used occasionally in this idiom (<a href='https://suttacentral.net/sn10.2/en/sujato#3.1'>SN 10.2:3.1</a>, <a href='https://suttacentral.net/thig13.4/en/sujato#2.3'>Thig 13.4:2.3</a>), which is apparently not attested in Sanskrit. The commentary explains <i lang='pi' translate='no'>vaṇṇa</i> here as “reason” (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>kāraṇa</i>). In each context, there is an apparently hidden circumstance that needs to be brought to light. I think it anticipates <i lang='pi' translate='no'>vaṇṇanā</i> in the sense of “commentary”, “explanation”; cf. English “gloss”. ",
    "sn9.14:5.3": "",
    "sn9.14:8.1": "The deity disavows dependence on humans and any mutual obligation that may entail. They gave advice freely. ",
    "sn9.14:8.2": ""
  },
